properties.Title: High Water Advisory Alert Issued For The Interlake
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for parts of the Interlake region due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up to date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-19T12:30:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-18T15:26:52-05:00, 55A746E1-B22F-6C43-AB59-8D1F2E1A1756
Area: Interlake region of Manitoba
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A short period of significant rainfall is expected. Total rainfall: localized areas of 20 to 30 mm in heavy downpours. Locations: eastern and southern Avalon Peninsula. Timespan: early this morning until midday today. Remarks: Rain will spread northward across the Avalon Peninsula early this morning with a risk of thundershowers over southern parts of the peninsula. Rainfall rates of 5 to 10 mm per hour are possible in the heaviest downpours. The precipitation is expected to taper to occasional showers or drizzle around noon. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-10-18T20:59:24-00:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A low pressure system tracking out of the northern Prairie provinces will spread snow into Whale Cove, Rankin Inlet, and Chesterfield Inlet today. The snow may be mixed at times with rain, which may limit accumulations initially, before precipitation intensifies tonight into Saturday. Total accumulations will likely be in the 10 to 15 cm range by the time the snow tapers off on Sunday. This snowfall warning may be expanded to Naujaat later today for heavy snowfall expected on Saturday into Sunday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-19T06:33:20-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T14:34:20-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1318903924.2019
Area: Rankin Region including Whale Cove, Chesterfield Inlet

properties.Title: Frost Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Frost may damage some crops in frost-prone areas. Temperatures have dropped to near the freezing mark in some places early this morning, but should rise quickly after sunrise. Temperatures are expected to drop to near the freezing mark once again tonight into Saturday morning in some areas. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and an intense low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce blizzard conditions today and tonight. The winds will gradually ease on Saturday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-19T04:02:13-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T12:03:13-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0683490124.2019
Area: Dempster

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of significant coastal rain and high-elevation snow is expected. Total rainfall including today's amounts: 60 to 90 mm near Natuashish and 35 to 60 mm near Nain. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm inland and over higher terrain. Timespan: this evening until Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Rain, at times heavy, is expected along the north coast of Labrador today through Sunday. Over the higher elevations inland, precipitation will fall as heavy accumulating snow until midday Saturday before changing to a mixture of rain and wet snow, which will then continue until Sunday afternoon. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Be prepared for possible winter conditions at higher elevations. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-10-19T10:47:17-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T18:48:17-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1028013162.2019
